In studies in the United States, there was a lot of contamination between control groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and have firm recommendations.
Another study, the European study, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had been screened and those who had not.
This study also showed, with a follow-up after 12 years, that we have between 30 and 40% more chance of having metastases if we are not tested.
So I recommend the test from age 50, or from age 40 if you have a direct parent who has already had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also more at risk.
The key is to make the right decision once we've detected cancer.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
It is really necessary to make the patient understand the degree of risk of his or her cancer, by offering him or her options, by not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not affect life in the long term, and by opting instead, in these cases, for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men in whom cancer is detected will not be treated because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
We're going to suggest that they do active surveillance and if the disease progresses, we're going to offer them treatment.
