Since 2009, in an attempt to "win hearts and minds" and carry out the impossible task of matching aid and offensive actions, a service of "civilo-military actions" of the Ministry of Defence (Cimic), abolished in 2012, has carried out, and had carried out by a small French NGO, numerous works of collective interest and agricultural rehabilitation actions in dozens of mountain villages.
This work, which is greedy of local labour, has helped to contain the insurgency: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and an increase in cultivable areas.
What will we leave to remember, after two billion euros of military spending?
A much smaller budget would contribute to the improvement of local living conditions, which are very harsh in these valleys, often more than 2,000 metres above sea level.
The Embassy received dozens of written requests for small agricultural achievements from local communities in Kapisa Province.
In order for them to free themselves from the insurgency led by foreign groups, which the farmers have told me they wish, small, well-controlled and directly affecting civil aid should be maintained for them.
A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
It's a new poker kick from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, it has decided to play its game.
Taking everyone short, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State granted this House an additional two months to complete its work.
Egypt has been relying almost two years on a provisional text, several times amended which undermines institutional stability and leads to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only deepened the divide in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic deliriousness", continuing to "traitor his word" and "pity the law".
On the side of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a way to put an end to the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible, speeding up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within two weeks.
A very short period of time which obliges the Brothers to give up their plans to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, this is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy as the challenge rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote favorably, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this resort to a hasty vote is due to the ultimatum of the Egyptian people: "Be you voting for my text, either I keep full powers", these are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It was in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamic majority, voted in favour of the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were missing.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, believing that they had not been able to present their views.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, replacement members, were added in haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it was most often unanimously that the articles were voted on.
Commentators also had fun that only one of the differences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the pendulum of the constituent was not well settled.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
Subject matter of all attention, article 2 remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to be able to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have allowed a stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their goodwill and their respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," the Liberals reply, who see it as just a communication coup.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
These include article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance of laws with sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the first fruits of a theocracy".
The Liberals' fears are also fuelled by the fact that the next president of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"For the time being, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of civil status.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system" tempers Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
Reference is made to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question could arise in the future as to the extent to which civilian judges are competent to rule on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extended powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced in comparison to what they were under the former regime.
Another contentious point is the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as requested by human rights associations.
The latter also expressed their concern about the text, which they considered to be liberticide.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences on freedom of expression, especially in the press.
In addition, there are no articles that echo the protection of women, says Human Rights Watch's Heba Morayef.
In her view, the only positive development was the prohibition of torture in article 36.
The word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian President was scheduled to speak last night on television, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
The head of state's supporters will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the greatness of Bible truths, modern comfort and wilderness.
Argoumenty i Fakty has retained five main reasons to go to Israel.
Go and worship the holy places
Make yourself a must: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who penetrates these "baptismal foundations" will be touched by divine grace.
As for Galilee, it is the earth of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he soothed the storm, or where the fishing was miraculous.
It was there that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
The believers travel through the Rue de la Souffrance or the Way of the Cross (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the courthouse), where the trial was held, then led by the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Anointing and the tomb.
This is where the Christian center of the world stands, symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to the Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem also houses the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wall of Lamentations which constitutes the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 B.C.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave there small words accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel high
Visit the ruins of Massada Fortress, an ancient refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 B.C. for his family.
These ruins are on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineers can get there by their own means.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this top full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont, which welcomes many tourists in the winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
Ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs want pagan gods to have once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth the detour.
First of all: the Israel Museum located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It houses the very ancient manuscripts of Qumran, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: the Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
The paintings of Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso are mainly exhibited.
In Acre, Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of casts of visitors and monitors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire sculptures by Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Yad Vashem Holocaust Museum or Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the children's memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter in total darkness.
Stars are shimmering.
You then hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
Israel's three major seaside resorts are on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each one offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, as the temperature of the water does not fall below 21° while the temperature of the air can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point of the Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure-coloured water contains brine and very easily holds the bathers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes surrounding it are of surreal beauty.
We come there to perform a treatment based on salt water, silt, curative sludge and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by the old town of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived here himself a long and happy life.
Tourists especially like to walk in the narrow alleyways which bear the name of the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile on you.
In Jaffa you will be able to meet newlyweds coming to do photoshoots of all Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre, "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, notably Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera shows.
Note to tourists
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer the dollars to the euro, as they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
With regard to urban transport, these are mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It's almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturdays.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturdays, markets, shops and public transport stop their activities.
And the workweek starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafés, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, scaly-free fish and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish dough, various sauces, ground chickpea balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are a lot of well-nourished cats walking around in the haughty air.
We can see them sleeping at night on the roofs of parked cars.
These cats love places that pass by and don't refuse to treat them.
Car rental varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
An entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The language of the numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mostly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists visited Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before visa cancellation on 9 February 2011.
"Who language has, in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists are debating what the law on compulsory language testing will give, fraudsters selling "false" certificates have already appeared in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are nationals of Central Asia: Tajikistan, Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan.
Their only goal is to make money to help their families who stayed at home.
Since 1 December, a law had entered into force and stipulated that every migrant worker would have to pass a Russian examination.
For the time being, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, promises the Federal Migration Service, the tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, knowledge of the language, but also of the history of Russia and the foundations of law, will have to be validated.
It will be necessary to validate his language knowledge in Russian in order to obtain and renew his work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt.
Persons who obtained educational certificates or diplomas prior to the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not covered by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be under the auspices of the Russian-speaking Pushkin Institute, the University of Peoples' Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions in Russia.
Immigrants will be able to take exams in all the cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already asked the question many times in the press: what will it give?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, the representatives of the migration service reply, this will reduce the number of people suffering from "slavery at work".
Many speak of defending the rights of migrant workers, explains the director of the Russian Federal Migration Service office in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
Protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in an overcrowded little house where he and dozens of his fellow men will torment each other for months without food and paper and will have to work between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"There is one thing we promise them, and when they arrive, we deceive them, we take their passports, and they don't get the salary they want," confirms Tolib Charipov, Head of the Directorate of Migration Services for the work of Tajikistan's Migration Service.
Don't argue with me, police officer!
However, many Central Asian nationals who want to come to Russia to earn money say that they do not only know the language of the country where they want to go, but also that they are writing with difficulty in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to attend even fair primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children without talking about dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to earn money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It's hard when you don't know the language, they confide.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the Language Act.
Examinations will be intended only for migrants with legal status.
Without status, there will be no review or formal work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or defense to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
And then you can get a fake recording quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
Russian police officers know that we have false documents, that we don't have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They ask us 100, 200 rubles, to buy cigarettes, tea," told journalists Umed Khushkadamov, a citizen of Tajikistan.
"Quick, don't skimp and buy yourself a beautiful work of art"
On the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that the registration documents of migrants were not the only ones to be false.
Several false language examination certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
The falsified papers come out of an ordinary colour printer.
Of course, their new owners did not have them for nothing: each migrant who thus hoped to facilitate the task of the examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
It is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Power representatives and human rights defenders agree that the short-term objective is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "paper sticks".
The authorities may give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the examination in the first instance the time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against civilian weapons carriers.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it is the shootings made during the weddings or the killing organised by Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven.
The police want to prohibit the wearing of rubber bullet weapons in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a weapons permit from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and the Fight against Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that the amendments to the Arms Act would be introduced to the State Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "tightening the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various firing centres, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a recorded weapon is minimal, said Vasiliy Lesnikov, a Russian lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC.
According to Ministry of the Interior statistics, over a six-month period in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services, while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are certain that the strengthening of civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market .
According to them, any weapon can be found today in Moscow for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior states that it controls the dissemination of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black arms market is supplied through several channels.
The main channels are five, says Victor Baranets, retired colonel who served ten years at the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot from a site taking arms orders
The first is "military trace", that is, weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians," explains Baranets.
The second type of black market weapons is those stolen from law enforcement by criminals.
Baranets explains that they are both weapons stolen from police stocks and weapons stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go for sale from military warehouses.
Many of the latter have often suffered explosions.
"Attested versions indicate that some fires were deliberately triggered to conceal the deficit," the former military officer explains.
For Baranets, the weapons manufacturers were responsible for something.
"We see private weapons factories that do not compete with international competition and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow," says one expert.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
A significant proportion of pistols and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a local production, sometimes craft production, a mafia formed and organizes the supply," adds the former military.
Where did the weapons come from?
The experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on this issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Specialists analysed the reports of the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, the criminal files and the public data of the weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the army and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found there "by fault of employees whose work is related to weapons," the report explains.
According to researchers, 17% of weapons come from military conflict sites, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture, and 5% come from "undercover searches".
A seller and consultant of an armory who asked to remain anonymous ensures that for a long time no one buys the weapons found by these clandestine search specialists; they are too old.
Most often, he says, sellers will pick up new goods from military warehouses.
The person buys a unit, such as a TT gun, through a sign.
We deliver it to him by passing the goods through a fence.
"He transports it to town and sells it for 900 € per unit with two chargers," he says.
"It is true that the police are aware of all cases, so when crimes are about to be solved, they make a purchase of control from illegal arms dealers," the seller adds.
"As in a luxury shop"
The seller and buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I looked at sites, blogs, until a guy showed up and offered to come to the Begovaya station where someone was going to take me in a "corner" to bargain.
The price of the gun, they gave it to me on the spot.
Victor Baranets as Military Observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the salesman. I know someone, but I don't trust him.
There are sellers in the markets, but there you also have to come by saying, for example, "From such a person, who asked me to pass on that his daughter lost a tooth".
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with a person I trust.
He only gives them to me because he knows I won't give it.
Newbies are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former militaryman Victor Baranets tried as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The patterns, according to him, have not changed.
We gave him a photo album in which there was "everything we want."
"I thought I was in a luxury store," recalls the military.
There is no secret to the buyer, explains Baranets, we can try everything.
As a potential customer, I'm not just buying, we're going with the forest salesman and we're setting up a target.
"I'm allowed to shoot and when I'm convinced that the gun works well, we start negotiating," the expert describes.
A shop from his couch
Search engines display sites and groups on Vkontakte where you can buy weapons "for different uses".
For this, there is no need for any documents and no one to meet.
"Just have a specific amount of money," we write in advertising on the website "Buy a gun or a combat machine gun".
Users leave their request and ask their questions.
