Šimon Ornest said: "In concert, we want to collect positive energy."
What do you think of the fact that in less than a month it should be the end of the world?
It's just one of those alarming news, the kind of traps we like to fall into.
In our band The Tap Tap, we laugh about it and we think that we are the only group able to collect a balance of positive energy in order to push back or prevent the end of the world.
In addition, in December you set up a very unique project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you present this project to our readers in more detail?
It is a charitable action that we have been preparing for two years.
We decided to use the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar announced for December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, on 20 December, three concerts will be held simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end almost as soon as the Mayan calendar on the island of Kiribati in the Pacific Ocean ends, in a time zone 12 hours ahead of us.
Who had that idea?
At first I think it was my idea, then we designed everything with our creator, Honza Augusta.
Apart from the fact that we want to collect enough positive energy to save the world, we also want together, with the public, to reflect on the state of the world we leave to our children.
At the end of the Maya calendar, we created a collection of unique items, including shoes, T-shirts, bags, and original keys against the end of the world, by buying them online at www.e-tap.cz people can also support us.
The Tap Tap band along with other performers also recorded an anthem against the end of the world which is titled "End of the World Cancelled " (in Czech "Konec světa zrušeno").
It is already very popular on YouTube, will we also hear it at these charity concerts?
Of course, everything at the end, at last, if we succeed and the end of the world does not take place ...
It will be sung simultaneously by all performers in all three concerts.
The hymns will also join at some point as part of a unique live programme on Czech television.
The lyrics of this song were written by Tom+Hanák who also holds the lead role of Jesus in the clip, Xindl X sings there as well...
How did you come to cooperate with them?
We collaborate with other personalities of the Czech show-biz, due to the fact that we organize numerous concerts and charity events...
We strive to involve them intensively in these projects.
It turned out that most of them are interested in such cooperation and that it amuses them.
What will the benefits of these concerts against the end of the world be for?
To equip the Studeo training centre, which is accessible to people with reduced mobility and which we have been working on in the framework of the Jedlička Institute, with the Tap association, and this for six years.
Teachers regularly visit the students of the Jedličkův Institute and offer them activities that interest and amuse them.
Students themselves do not have the means to go to classes, we try to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the construction of the Jedlička Institute, we will transfer this project to a new independent building.
Several music groups and performers will be on stage at each of these concerts?
By what criteria did you choose them?
We have tried to develop a program for all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague, will stage Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustrator with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiů Suchý.
Details can be found at www.kpks.cz.
Are you also preparing for other "mega-events" of this kind in the future?
In May, we will play for the first time in the spring of Prague; here too, we will surely prepare a quality programme with interesting guests.
We'd also like to play next year in the Czech Republic's house in New York and personally, once I'm there in the United States, I'd like to combine concerts in Washington and Chicago.
Your international projects are minimalist, so far you have played for example in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage the organization and logistics of your tours?
It's not so bad that it looks like it's at first sight.
We have five members in an electric chair whose vehicles must travel in the hold, of course we also carry a lot of luggage and boxes of instruments....
So far everything has gone more or less well, ČSA and British Airways were always perfectly prepared for us, they surprised me more than once.
Even in Moscow, where we recently returned, everything happened without problems.
With your trips abroad, you can compare how these countries differ in terms of accessibility for people with reduced mobility, public attitudes towards people with disabilities and so on.
What have been your experiences so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than at home, we have just witnessed in Moscow that in the east all are still only in an initial phase.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is still very little accessible to people with disabilities; it is not yet common for a person to travel alone in an electric chair in the centre of the city.
They do not yet consider it obvious to give priority to a person in a wheelchair in an elevator.
Fortunately, there too, an association is being set up to draw attention to the problems of persons with disabilities.
How do we still have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are a lot of things we're still late for...
It is important to note that improvements and improvements still depend on the efforts of the people concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with a heavy disability to move alone in public spaces; they can go to the toilet, the museum, anywhere...
It is not very common there that a large number of people with disabilities actively participate in social life, on this point you, The Tap Tap, are on the contrary at the forefront of progress!
Respect for the public and ease of access are one thing, but the situation will really start to change when we have among us famous sportsmen, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers.
For the time being, these are only isolated cases of people who have a strong will.
The Tap Tap band is currently very popular, let's go back a few years, what prompted you in 1998 to create this band?
I started working as an educator at the Jedlička Institute, where I found myself surrounded by many young people willing to invest in something.
And since I myself am a musician (I play, among other things, saxophone), with a colleague, we have created a music activity.
And then, over time, as our moderator, L.A. Angelovič, says, we lost control of the situation (laughs).
Success has only happened in recent years, if I'm not mistaken?
It's true that creating connections with well-known singers and working actively to promote the band helped us.
We understood that if a job is not visible, it is as if it did not exist in the background.
Thanks to EU grants, we can also afford quality teachers, equipment and so on.
Did you have the goal of reaching such a level with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt that there was a potential to change things.
The show business is full of stuff that copy each other.
In a way, it makes sense: everything that is new is accepted with caution and it lasts for a long time.
Rare are the original projects, and I dare to say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us for the first time is naturally pity, it's natural ...
But pity is totally useless, because people with disabilities are not suffering beings, abandoned by all, that we must take pity on.
They are people who can live a life in their own right and flourish, provided they have the necessary means, of course.
I often say that when people with disabilities manage to achieve something, it is not just a step forward for them but for the whole of society.
Isn't your success also due to the fact that you are a demanding leader, as you are qualified by many people?
If we are to do quality work, we must be intransigent in many areas and require discipline.
But I think it's quite normal.
Some people arrive at our house with a romantic vision and head in the clouds and, when they realize that they have to come to rehearsals twice a week, take preparatory classes and spend a lot of time on the roads for concerts, they quickly lose their enthusiasm.
But it works the same way in every group that wants to work and achieve goals.
The Tap Tap group currently has 20 members.
How many of them were already there in 1998?
Only one, L.A. Angelovič.
We're an open group, people go in and out, there's nothing we can do about it.
Our doors are always open to those who want or would like to join us.
This will be the case the day before the scheduled end of the world day, Thursday, December 20, 2012 from 9 p.m.
