The film Argo: when everything goes to the worst, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of Islamist students stormed the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who had been supporting his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously undermined the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages.
It was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, a blow further aggravated by the fiasco of the attempted release of the hostages by force.
The sequestered diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate aroused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle strongly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered America a small victory.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated events, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran thanks to a rocky cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who came to make spots for the shooting of a science fiction show film.
Combination of genera
Exfiltration expert Tony Mendez's plan required Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialist magazines reported on this film project, press conferences were held and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation long remained secret, the film being based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
On the one hand, it is a realistically designed political thriller but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful blow, a treachery - as, for example, in the Ocean's raised, Twelve and Thirteen trilogy.
The atmospheres follow each other: sequences of Tehran in documentary style (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed in the film, there are no great differences),
lighter Hollywood passages, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
And then scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting ceased to elicit ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film that does not take place in his home city, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the features that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the embassy's fall is impressive by its clarity which also suggests confusion and unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake shooting team in Tehran's bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to settle for a subject that actually offered few thrilling scenes, in the cinematic sense of the term.
He does very well, he sometimes adds some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is ruled out by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the airstrip is drawn enough by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in his dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events at too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood coopers, their characters would have earned a bigger place and they are not, far from it, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it allows itself to be seen with moderate interest, enjoying the realization and retro style of the 70s.
He trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of yet another story, in a certain way, unfinished to date, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, it does the job.
Rules to inflate balloons, bananas and circus
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which conducts an annual public inquiry into the most absurd banking charges, has now decided to launch the competition for the regulation or ideas from the most absurd "EU workshop".
"The fact that the EU has recently planned to adopt a quota of 40 per cent for the management of large European companies has led to our decision," said the newspaper Právo, the organiser of this survey, Patrik Nacher.
Among the absurdities mentioned, there is already, for example, the recent decision of the European Court to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
So far, however, women have benefited from life insurance rates because they represent, objectively, less risk to insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other such incredible idea of "the EU workshop".
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013", informed Nacher.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the requirement to add organic components to fuels, which has adverse environmental consequences, or the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers, solely because they contain a relatively small amount of a hazardous substance, or the hen cage size directive, which has led to higher egg prices.
Criticism has also been expressed in the past against the de facto ban on the use of the term "butter to spread" or the withdrawal of the sale of conventional bulbs.
Quality bananas must have a size of 14 centimetres.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or group of states (for example, the Czech Republic currently imposes the demands of its banks by threatening to use its veto power).
The interests of pressure groups are also, for example, at the root of the fact that bananas in the Union must not be of a size less than 14 cm or have an "abnormal curve".
The European Commission has defended itself by arguing that it is merely harmonising non-homogeneous national standards that complicate trade.
Standards for fruit and vegetables have been relaxed despite opposition from some States, claiming that existing directives result in food wastage.
The first prize may be awarded in this investigation to last year's EU regulation that must include a warning on inflatable balloons that children under the age of 8 should not inflate without adult supervision.
The EU referred to a U.S. investigation that balloons are the leading cause of child death from suffocation among toys.
A similar restriction applies to children under the age of 14 when blowing in fair trumpets.
At home, too, we have weird ideas.
The following rule concerning European civil servants themselves is quite absurd: because of the sensitivity of this topic to Greece, anyone with an official position in the EU cannot use the name "Macedonia" and instead must speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the association "Let Do" of liberal economists, the Bankovnípoplatky.com server named in this survey, in addition to some absurdities mentioned above, the EU regulation on the volume of food supplies in the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for food supplies that could be found in the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the volumes fixed for canned mushrooms and, as a result, risked a heavy fine.
The organizers of this survey found the idea of paying money to certain countries because they do not have access to the sea and the idea of granting a grant to apply for grants to be granted.
These ideas, however, do not originate in Brussels but in Prague.
"The fact that we don't have a sea handicaps us.
We are going to ask the European Union for a refund." In autumn 2004, the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) said.
He argued that, as a result of our wheat production, and as a result of so-called "interventionist" purchases, the state had found itself with full stocks that it had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us millions of euros, because the Czech Republic is far from the ports.
In the end, the European Commission responded positively to Czech demand and organised a tender for the purchase of wheat from countries without maritime access.
Grants for obtaining grants were proposed to municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development, headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), and these were to be used, in concrete terms, to draw up applications for grants granted by Brussels.
The EU states: "Weird regulations are rare".
While the regulations are often criticized in the Member States, many experts believe that the EU's efforts to regulate and improve the effectiveness of the Union's functioning and its overall development are more deserving of praise.
More serious, for example, according to experts, is the problem of the use of EU grants for projects which have absolutely nothing to do with strengthening European integration, but which were imposed by the Member States in the budget negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other EU countries, has to fight in Brussels for the right to use specific names for these traditional products (a struggle which it does not always win) arouses strong emotions among Czechs.
If at the end of six years of battle against the Germans and Austrians, the Czechs successfully defended the name "Olomoucké tvarрусскийky", as far as the name "Tuzemský rum" which dates back to us in the 19th century, our producers had to replace it with the name "Tuzemák".
