The architects of the MVRDV firm prove that the real adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To be convinced, it is enough to contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, at last something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist in a large nearby company, tells us: "Yes, it is indeed beautiful, this building".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one goes to one of these ringuard libraries of their own free will, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that is not attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, has a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore a few neurons to the brains, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty small miniature painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive has remained limited.
Thus the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control over the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, from Rotterdam's architect office MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of witty and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and presented himself to the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a squealing on his face.
And while the jury members were still looking at each other, disconcerted and waving their shoulders, Maas, brazen, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make them a pyramid, and ended his speech supported by militant arguments by one: "common love!"
Here it is, my proposal for the book mountain of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the EUR 30 million mountain sprang from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and adjoining houses for a total of 50 homes.
In early November, the book mountain received the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project was selected for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
Thus, this small, dull village, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall of a staggering uglyness, whose white facades invite to think that they are home to a dairy, has been enriched by a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Path to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Of course, an elevator carries you to the heart of the massif, but the true joys of reading and architecture open to you when you walk the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant lamps speak unequivocally the language of the municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking at public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books, and more books.
"Normally, library shelves are located along the façade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," says Willy Maas.
We completely changed the classic spatial configuration and opened the spaces for reading from inside to outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been neatly laid out: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental center and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes panelling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircase ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found in a Frisian agricultural enterprise an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membrane with a thickness of one millimetre has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're saving time.
The fine membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into four centimetres thick plates.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and is transformed into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 metres, the literary café offers stunning views of the city, as well as Dutch croquettes and potted ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal level of humidity of the literary mountain air.
Gifts for the new soul
"It's incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model ecological project," says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is controlled by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even on days of fine weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted across the glass façade serve as a sun visor, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
The completely automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already ventured to enter the new library.
Lisette Verhaig too was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "at last recovered soul".
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure has made it possible to fill the gaps in the library that was not yet fully stocked (today, it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I believe that our invitation created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has reached the master discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse wrote a new page of literary history.
Even though she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer State status with the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, without however being too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 insurgency in Libya, Germany had also chosen to abstain in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany have any difficulties in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy as it were defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore encounter several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that they are still trying to find this role, but are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for Germans?
It shows the will to adopt positions beyond those of the United States and European partners, including on national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the Middle East conflict and its abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to clash with public opinion, but also with the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a determining factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive factor in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany harm its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I believe that the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be even more respected.
Indeed, Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear vote.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you observe the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm for Netanyahu's policy.
Is Germany having difficulty reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States with the position of the major European partners?
I don't think it makes things easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore be part of a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
That is what they are currently doing in the question of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will take on a role as a locomotive in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This has always been a delicate issue.
But in my view, the Germans are well aware of the fact that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself playing a leading role on the international stage, does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does it still have difficulty taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country is still struggling to play a more important role.
If we look, for example, at the euro crisis, we notice that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things any easier for the Germans.
In fact, it is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
She has to deal with a wide variety of neighbours and opinions, and it's not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only diminishing, but at the moment the EU is not filling this void, so who remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Trademark protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is this really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the undertaking bearing its name cannot lodge a complaint.
