Bradley Manning has not complained of ill-treatment, state prosecutors.
Prosecutors are trying to counter the claims of ill-treatment allegedly suffered by Bradley Manning during detention.
The trial concerns Manning's detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence wants to close the case on the grounds that Manning's kidnapping was carried out under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to demonstrate on Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of causing the biggest leak of confidential information in the history of the U.S. Army -- missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
In cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein claimed that recordings of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a motion requiring that the Manning case be closed on the grounds that the kidnapping took place in very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning testified his desire to commit suicide while in detention.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while serving in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning had been their source.
During Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers had filled out after meeting with Manning, during his detention in Quantico Military Prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment his guards had given him was "excellent" and that the treatment he had received in the prison was overall "very professional."
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his treatment in prison, Fein said.
Manning responded that he had orally expressed concerns about certain issues and that visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the issues raised.
"They wrote "no problem" (after addressing the concerns), and yet it did not mean that I had not raised any problems," Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during a January 2011 interview with the special commission that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to change his restrictive status indicating a "risk of injury".
Members stated that they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was okay, and I wanted to be removed from my status... in order to enjoy a better quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison of the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He stated that he considered suicide while in Kuwait and fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was going on in the rest of the world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning stated that he had spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had were mattresses, blankets, flip-flops, clothing and glasses.
He tried to stay in motion, because sleeping or lying down during the day was contrary to the rules.
Manning also specified that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned around at night, they woke him up so that they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his Thursday testimony -- that after being forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other detainees one morning, during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning stated that he had inferred from the order of his guard that he should let go of his cover that might have hidden his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to let go of it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he was forced to sleep naked the night before, as he would have tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning allegedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or flip-flops to hurt himself, but that he had not done so.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account the experiences he experienced during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he is to be convicted before a court martial, a trial that is expected to take place early next year.
The defense stated that Manning is considering pleading guilty to the least serious crimes and fighting for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing should resume this weekend, with prosecutors who should argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon confirmed that Manning was imprisoned in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include the theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information relating to national defence.
If all charges are laid, he is liable to life imprisonment.
