The hardest job in the world: Kawah Ijen's human mule
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make their living carrying sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of Indonesia's Java island.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphur gas from the earth's internals solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large sulphur rocks, which weigh nearly 70 kilos in total, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through steep paths.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano that peaks at 2,386 meters of altitude, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a tortoise-like pace, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a fatal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents of euro for each kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once at the top, he makes a way between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and painfully carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the scale that a mining company installed a little below at 1,850 meters altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to the petrochemical industry at 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents), since this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to manufacture candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes him 3 hours and finishes exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is three times what it would gain in the fields.
"The income of the miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)", states the bearer who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was Rs 75,000 (6.20 euros) a day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned near his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hinduists, and I brought her back to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and her eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he spent three of his life defying danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulfur has already begun to charge him the bill although he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
