AIDS-related deaths are now due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed with the HIV test.
"It was as if the sky had fallen on my head," he said, referring to the time of the announcement, that the doctor had tried to make "less painful", in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to inquire about it and his relentlessness was such that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, where there was a lot of doubt, little choice of treatment and more stigma.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was speechless."
In those days, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "exhausted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, in all cases after the first reported cases, "the great victory is today that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the population in general is exactly the same," said HCG's head of the HIV unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, and he takes as his reference that this information was validated in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
The HIV/AIDS infectiologist and expert, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a deadly disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of immune system allocation of patients at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those not using drugs: up to 30 years for CD4 levels of 200 and up to 50 years for those reaching 500 CD4 levels.
To put it simply, it means that for someone who would be diagnosed with HIV positive at age 25, "as long as he stays under control, can live without problems up to 75 years," the scientist interviewed explained.
In order to put this progress in context, it is important to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans is now on average 76 years.
While it is true that mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died from AIDS has increased from 6.678 in 2007 to 4.862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of the patients registered on the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths until May of this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
Then why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem comes from access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the past 12 years at least, we've never run out of drugs, the problem is that patients get to very advanced stages because they don't know they're infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
It gives us an indisputable fact "nine out of ten patients arrive while they already have an opportunistic infection, what is needed to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to carry out earlier diagnoses and, to do so, we must offer screening tests in a massive way, to all those who request it".
Specialists and members of the Jalisco State Council for AIDS Prevention (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as do patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to do his test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and despite his young age, he was already carrying AIDS and suffering from Kaposi sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, it's better if I have fun three times a week," they say, "it's not my case.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medication.
To date, his parents only know that he is suffering from cancer.
I have a normal life, just like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILEnio JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the march of World AIDS Day.
Whether they take the test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV-positive and the better, and if they already have the diagnosis, they need to know that we can live like everyone else, by being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the 2012 battle against AIDS.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programmes and ordinary citizens, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has embraced the cause of HIV.
And the biggest thing is prevention.
In all places dedicated to this, "the distribution of condoms has actually been increased, before we were given one or two, now we are given packages of one hundred, it is very good, but it results, that still today, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", asked with sarcasm and value judgments by social workers, guidance counsellors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers do not want to hear, assures the journalist.
It proposes to reorient this inefficient distribution; that condoms not only be sold at counters, but be found in public toilet dispensers and in places frequented by young people.
It is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it a question of paying them the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González had replied when asked if there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
"This is not how sexuality works, the best is to provide condoms to people already sexually active," he stressed.
The figures in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The State is the 4th state of the country in number of new and cumulative AIDS cases and 13th for the number of HIV patients.
92% of infections occur by sexual means, 6% by blood and 2% by perinatal means.
It is estimated that 50,000 people are living with HIV, since for each recorded case, there are 4 or 5 people who do not know.
A judgment ratified on appeal by a United States court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group's debt through commercial bankruptcy in Mexico. The scenario creates a bad precedent for all domestic companies with branching in the neighbouring country and with solvency problems.
It therefore seems that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with the star banner, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the June 15 judgment of Judge Harlin Hale of the Court of Bankruptcy for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies defenceless in the face of the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico's leading glass manufacturer to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court on the basis of three inconsistencies.
First, while the judge of the case points out that creditors must register under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeal, sitting in New Orleans, states that the main proceeding is formalized commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
Indeed, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law had been established for that purpose by taking the American Law Institute as an arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment establishes that without the intercompany vote, recognised in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts contracted by Vitro's subsidiaries towards the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, Vitro's case is not the first to use this plan.
Here there are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcy.
Moreover, what is certain is that, since the votes of the subsidiaries remained, in any case Vitro's creditors who fought against this in the U.S. courts, i.e. "Vulture" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained the majority.
The vote would have been 45 to 37.
A data omitted by the appellate court.
On the other hand, Vitro has been blamed for the difficult situation he had encountered since 2008 without stopping at the serious economic crisis facing the United States, passing on the costs to the country.
For the time being, the González Sada family society will appeal to the same court of appeal to have the vote taken in its entirety, i.e. with the five magistrates, since only three had voted.
The insurance remedy will demand non-prosperity and requires review of the trial by a higher court, in this case the Supreme Court of Justice of the United States.
What is more serious is that the court ignored a document sent by the Mexican government on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the Court") in which Vitro's procedure under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act was detailed, noting that this freed him from the conventions signed by both countries to bring it to the same level as paragraph 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, he pointed out that the country had adhered to the United Nations Commission's principles on international trade, i.e. the rules for cross-border insolvency cases, which ensured fairness for debtors and creditors.
Carmbling of two parts: they circle Vitro and they circle the country.
